 car was old and needed a paint job. He could have taken it to a car dealership or to a body shop, but he wanted this to be a surprise for his son. So he painted it himself. 

#  The Big Day

On the big day, Dennis woke up early and put the finishing touches on the car. He used a blow dryer to make the paint job last longer and used a wire brush to remove any bird droppings from the body. He vacuumed the car and put a little oil on the wheels to keep them from squeaking as he drove off. 

After eating breakfast, he drove the car to Robert's house and parked it in the driveway. He walked up the walkway and rang the doorbell. 

#  The Surprise!

When Robert opened the door, he was surprised to see his old car sitting in the driveway. "Dennis! What did you do?" Robert asked. 

"I told you I was going to paint the car. I used your father's tools to do it!" Dennis replied. 

"But it's my car! I want to drive it!" Robert exclaimed.

"Well, you can drive it when we go get gas. I put some gas in it, but you have to let it run for a minute to let the gas tank empty," Dennis said.

"OK, Dad," Robert said. He ran to his room and came back with his dad's car keys. He ran back outside and opened the car door. He got in and put the key in the ignition. The car started right up! "Wow! This is great, Dad!" Robert said.

"You're right, it is great. You finally have your own car," Dennis replied.

Robert drove the car to the gas station. He filled the tank and put some gas in the car. When he got back home, he took the car for a test drive. He drove around the neighborhood and back. He was amazed at how well the car drove. It was like it had always been his. 

#  Back in the Garage

Dennis and Robert took turns painting the car every weekend for a month. When it was time for them to stop, it was nice and shiny. They were proud of their work. 

Dennis and Robert took the car to the car wash. As they were getting out, they noticed something shiny on the ground. They picked it up and realized it was a penny. They had forgotten to take the car to the wash station at the end of the last weekend. 

#  A New Coin

They put the penny in the ashtray and drove to the carnival. They had a great time. Robert was amazed at all the rides and games. They left the carnival around dinnertime and headed home. 

When they got home, Robert put the car in the garage. He got out and locked the car, and then he went inside. When he got to his room, he put his penny on his dresser. He was going to show it to his friends the next day. 

#  The Next Day

Robert got ready for school. He put his penny on his desk and headed downstairs. When he walked into the living room, he saw his dad was watching the news. He was surprised to see his dad was still up. "Hey, Dad, what are you doing up? It's Sunday."

"I can't sleep. I was thinking about how I used to work at the carnival when I was a kid. I used to love going to the carnival with my dad. We used to take the car to the car wash, and when we got home, I would put my penny on my dresser. It would sit there until the next day when I would show it to my friends," Dennis said.

Robert was shocked. His dad had never mentioned the car wash or the penny before. 

#  A New Tradition

The next day, Robert took his penny to school. He showed it to his friends. They all knew someone who had a penny. They all started a new tradition. Every Sunday, they would take their penny out of their wallets and show it to their parents. 

Robert had a great time with his friends and his penny. His penny went to school with him and came back home with him. When he got home from school, he would put his penny on his dresser. It was part of his new tradition. 

#  A Lifetime of Memories

Robert grew up and had kids of his own. He told his kids the story of how he got his penny. His kids all had friends with pennies, and their kids had friends with pennies. This tradition continued for many years. Robert had a lifetime of memories with his penny.

The Value Proposition is a way of expressing the value that you provide to your customers. It's an elevator pitch for your business.

'She's doing very well, she just finished her Masters and is now working as a research analyst, which she loves' Felicia replied.

The car was packed with her, Emily and Matt, as well as her bags and suitcase. Felicia was looking forward to the time she'd be able to spend with them.

'I'm not sure, I'm going to speak to Greg about it' Emily replied.

Greg was a career advisor at the local university and Felicia knew he would be able to give Emily some good advice.

'That's great, you should really consider what you want to do' Felicia said.

She was surprised to hear Emily hadn't made up her mind yet. She had always been so focused on her studies and now she was done she didn't seem to know what to do with herself.

'I will, thanks' Emily replied.

 give it a try.

Lindsey finished her meal and drove to work. She had a new recipe she wanted to try. She decided to make it the next day for dinner.

!

Fried rice with duck and cashews in spicy sauce

 name: Fried Rice with Duck and Cashews in Spicy Sauce

 name: Kung Pao Fried Rice

 includes: rice, duck, cashews, onions, peppers, sriracha sauce, and oyster sauce

 timing: 10 mins

 makes: 2 servings

 cost: under $10

 rating: 8 out of 10

 tips: You can use chicken or pork for the duck. You can use green peas instead of the duck if you'd like. You can use a larger portion of cashews in spicy sauce if you like more heat.

 comments: The spicy sauce had a nice kick to it. The sweetness from the rice and the spice from the sauce complemented the duck and cashews well. Lindsey enjoyed it.

 recipe: Fried Rice with Duck and Cashews in Spicy Sauce

Ingredients

2 tablespoons vegetable oil

1 tablespoon minced garlic

1 teaspoon grated ginger

ยฝ cup sliced and peeled carrots

ยฝ cup sliced and peeled red onions

ยฝ cup sliced and peeled red bell peppers

ยฝ cup sliced and peeled and de-seeded tomatoes

ยฝ cup sliced and peeled and de-seeded cucumbers

ยฝ cup sliced and peeled and de-seeded green onions

1 cup cooked rice

2 tablespoons oyster sauce

2 tablespoons soy sauce

2 tablespoons rice wine

1 teaspoon sriracha sauce

ยฝ cup raw cashews

Directions

1. In a wok or large skillet, heat the oil over medium heat. Add the garlic, ginger, and carrots. Stir-fry for 2 minutes.

2. Add the onions, bell peppers, tomatoes, cucumbers, and green onions. Stir-fry for 3 minutes.

3. Add the cooked rice, oyster sauce, soy sauce, rice wine, and sriracha. Toss to coat the rice well.

4. Remove from the heat. Add the cashews and toss to coat.

5. Transfer to a bowl and serve.

In summary, people like to help others if they perceive that the other person is open to receiving help, and that the help offered is of low complexity.

The following sections describe different ways to help others, based on the Helper Type.

### The Protector

The Protector is motivated to help others because they want to protect people from harm or unpleasant situations.  They tend to avoid risks and want to ensure that others are safe.  They are concerned about their personal image and don't want to be associated with anything negative.

As a Protector, you might worry that helping others could harm your reputation, or that you might do something that could be perceived negatively by others.  As a result, you might hesitate to help others, even though you want to do so.

Helping others can be hard for Protectors, because it requires you to step away from your own concerns and put the other person's needs ahead of yours.  You need to be able to let go of your own worries and to put the other person's needs ahead of your own.

The following example, shows a Protector helping a Helper.

### Example of a Protector Helping a Helper

But Benjamin fixed it up and made it beautiful, just like he did with this house he was building for Joseph.  memorable. I wish I could remember the name of the tree that we used for the house. It was a massive tree, and we had to cut it down to build the house. _โZach_

_Dear Zach,_

_โBen_

_โBen_

# THE BEST TREEHOUSE IN THE WOODS

_by Benjamin_

I remember the day that my family built our treehouse. My parents had been saving money for a long time, and it was the first time in many years that we'd had enough money to do something really special. We'd been talking about building a treehouse for months, and we'd finally saved enough money to buy the materials and start construction.

My brothers and I worked with our dad to cut down the tree and haul it away. We worked until it was dark, and then we helped our mom drag the treehouse into the clearing. It was a lot of work, but it was well worth it to see our excitement when we finally got it all situated. We were going to have a great time in our treehouse!

We had a lot of fun building the treehouse. We used the money that my parents had saved to buy the wood and the nails and screws, and we did most of the work ourselves. We cut the wood with a handsaw and hammered the nails with a hammer my dad had made. We did have one tool that we couldn't make or buy: a tape measure. We used a string and a stick to measure the distances between the trees, and we used a rope to help us hoist the treehouse into place.

We finished our treehouse just in time for the holidays. We were so excited to have a new place to play during the summer. We'd spend hours in the treehouse, and we'd fill the time by reading books or playing board games. We were lucky to have such a great place to stay during the summer.

One morning, my dad woke up early and went outside to work in the yard. He was going to use our chainsaw to cut some wood for the fireplace. My brothers and I were still in bed when we heard a loud crash. We ran outside to see what had happened.

Reception
"The Stare" was well received by critics. On review aggregation website Rotten Tomatoes, the episode has a 93% approval rating, based on 15 reviews with an average score of 8.2 out of 10. The site's consensus reads: "The Stare, while a bit on the predictable side, offers a thought-provoking, well-executed take on the paranoid thriller, thanks in no small part to a nuanced performance from Michael Pitt."

Caroline Siede of The A.V. Club awarded the episode a "Aโ", writing, "There's something deeply unnerving about 'The Stare,' the latest episode of Hannibal, that really gets under your skin." She praised the performances and the direction, calling the opening sequence "terrifying". Siede did, however, criticise the episode for relying too much on the "twist" ending, adding, "If youโve been paying close attention to the show so far, you might guess that something is off about Will and Hannibal, but itโs not until the end of the episode that we actually see that something is off. Itโs a bit too convenient and a bit too easily guessable."

Matt Fowler of IGN rated the episode an "8.5/10", writing, "What's most impressive about 'The Stare' is how it manages to create a sense of unease despite Hannibal's wit and charm." He was critical of the reveal of Hannibal as the killer, but praised the rest of the episode, particularly Michael Pitt's performance, as well as the direction and cinematography.

TV Fanatic's Dan Fox awarded the episode 4.5 stars out of 5, writing, "There's a lot to like in 'The Stare', but what really made it great was the small moments that made you feel like you were really there." He felt that the episode did a good job of building character relationships, and praised the performances and direction.

The episode was ranked as the fourth best episode of the first season by Entertainment Weekly, and was selected by Time as one of the 10 best TV episodes of 2015.

 Paige and John sat down at the table.
 "So, what's new?" John asked.
 "Well, I've been working on my college essay," Paige said.
 "Oh yeah? What's it about?"
 "Well, I was thinking about how I've been able to grow so much as a person since I met you. And I realized that a big part of that was because of the time we spend together."
 "That's nice," John said.
 "Yeah, but it still feels a little empty without a topic for the college essay," Paige said.
 "I'm not sure what you're looking for," John said.
 "I want to write about how I've been able to overcome my fears," Paige said.
 "Well, you've told me that you're afraid of heights, right?"
 "Yeah, that's true. And it's something I've thought about a lot over the last year."
 "I think I might be able to help you with that," John said.
 Paige's eyes lit up.
 "Really? How?"
 "Well, I know this great place in Colorado that has a big cliff with a view of the mountains. We could go there for the weekend and you can work on your fear in a safe environment."
 Paige smiled.
 "That sounds great! When are we going?"
 "Let me check my calendar and I'll get back to you," John said.
 Paige smiled and put her hands on the table.
 "Anything else I can help you with?" John asked.
 Paige thought for a moment.
 "Well, I'm not sure how to ask this, but I was wondering if you'd be my date to my cousin's wedding next month."
 John's eyes widened.
 "That would be amazing! When is the wedding?"
 "It's in a couple of weeks. But I already have your ticket and everything. It would just be you and me."
 John smiled.
 "I'd love to go with you. I haven't been to a wedding in a long time, but I remember how fun it is."
 Paige smiled.
 "Great. I'll let my family know and we'll plan our trip."
 John stood up.
 "I'll go start the car. You finish getting ready."
 Paige got up from the table and walked into the living room.
 She took a deep breath and let it out slowly. She walked over to the window and looked out at the street. She smiled. She was about to go to Colorado with John. And she was going to write about how she'd overcome her fear of heights. She turned around and walked back into the kitchen.
 "John, I'm ready. Let's go!"
 John and Paige got in the car and started driving to John's apartment.
 "So, what are we going to do today?" Paige asked.
 "Well, I have a few errands to run, but I can take you to lunch if you'd like."
 "That would be great. I'm starving," Paige said.
 John drove them to a small Italian restaurant.
 "So, what do you want to drink?"
 "I'll have a glass of red wine, if you don't mind," Paige said.
 John nodded and ordered their meals. Paige took a sip of her wine and enjoyed the taste.
 "So, tell me more about this wedding," John said.
 "It's my cousin Julia's wedding. She's been planning it for a couple of years now. And she finally found a dress that she likes."
 "That's wonderful. I'm so happy for her," John said.
 Paige smiled.
 "Thanks. It's a small wedding, just family and close friends. And there's going to be a lot of food, so I hope I can fit into my dress."
 John laughed.
 "You'll be fine. You look great the way you are."
 Paige blushed.
 "Thanks. I just need to stay away from the buffet."
 John laughed again.
 "So, how long have you guys been dating?"
 "Almost two years now. John is the best guy I've ever met. He's kind, considerate, funny, and we have a lot in common."
 "What was it like breaking up with Greg?" Paige asked.
 "It was hard. But John made me realize how much better this could be. I'm so glad I met him."
 John noticed Paige's phone was vibrating.
 "Is that your phone?"
 Paige nodded.
 "It's my sister. I have to take this."

items.prompt: Kyle loves the flavor of apricots but Matthew likes plums better. _ couldn't wait for apricot season.
items.response:
I made a batch of the recipe as written but with dried plums instead of the suggested dried apricots. Everyone loved the recipe either way! โKarenB
 went with dried plums instead of apricots. I love this recipe! It's super easy, only requires a few ingredients, and the pecan-cinnamon flavor is amazing. I will definitely be making this again and again! โlindsayh34

* * *

   Super Fast and Easy

* * *

* * *

Ingredients

* * *

2 tablespoons butter

2 tablespoons firmly packed brown sugar

1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon

1/4 cup chopped pecans

2 (8.5 ounce) boxes ladyfingers

1/3 cup sugar

3 tablespoons water

2 cups sliced dried plums

1/2 cup orange juice

* * *

Directions

  1. Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F.
  2. In a small saucepan, melt the butter over low heat. Stir in the brown sugar and cinnamon. Remove from the heat and stir in the pecans.
  3. Place the ladyfingers in a 9x13 inch baking pan, cut side up. In a small bowl, mix 1/3 cup sugar and the water. Drizzle over the ladyfingers. Spoon the butter mixture over the ladyfingers.
  4. Top with the dried plums. Pour the orange juice over the dried plums.
  5. Bake for 10-15 minutes. Serve warm.

 "I'm a web developer," Emily replied, "I help create and maintain websites for businesses."

 "That sounds really fun! I always wanted to do that when I was in school. Do you have any cool stories about that? Like, about how you helped someone set up their website?"

with a couple of other youtube channels. I have been following her channel for a couple years now and have learned so much about color, design and art in general. She recently did a paint along using one of my all time favorite movies, star wars. I loved this movie as a child and still love it now as an adult. I decided to start the process of re-watching the series after seeing this video and am currently on episode 5. I decided to use this episode because it is the one where luke meets han solo. I chose to paint han solo because it was the first character luke meets and it would be cool to paint a character from a movie that i watched as a child. I chose to paint him in my usual style which is a mix of traditional and digital. I chose to paint him in a style i call "trad digital" which is a mix of traditional media with a modern twist. This is what i was thinking of when i read the description of this challenge.
 my process starts with a base layer of yellow ochre gesso. i then applied that to the cold press watercolor paper using a brush to rough up the surface a bit. i then applied a thin wash of cad yellow medium. this is a traditional yellow paint, but it is thin enough that i can add water to it and it becomes a wash. i love this paint for this type of painting as it is very flexible. i wanted to apply a few thin lines of paint to the figure to show the shape of the body. i used a clean brush to do this. next i wanted to do some cross hatching on the body to show the shape of the clothing. i used a dry brush to apply this paint. next i wanted to add a bit of red to the hair and chest. this i did with a small brush and some cad red medium. i wanted to do a wash over the legs and hands to show the environment he is from. next i wanted to do some more cross hatching on the hands and legs to show the shape of the clothing. this is where i ran into trouble. i had already washed over the hands and legs the red, so the red wasnt showing up on my dry brush. i tried rewetting the dry brush, but this made the lines too thick. i also tried adding water to the wash i had on the body, but this made the yellow ochre gesso underneath show through. this was a tough one, but i decided to go with it and let the art speak for itself. i am happy with the results, but would have liked to have been able to do the hands and legs in the same wash as the body. i will take this lesson into the next piece i do, but i am happy with how this one turned out. thanks for stopping by and watching. i hope you have fun watching and painting along with me. i am always open to suggestions for future videos. peace out and stay creative, steve.

items.response:
I'm not a small person, but his place is always too small for me. He has a son who is older than me, and he is always asking me to do things. One time, he made me sleep in his bed with him. It was so small, and I felt like a big person in it. I hate that man. I hate his son. I wish they would disappear from this earth. I hope they both die of some horrible disease. I want to be free of them. I want to be free of everyone and everything that is not Harry.

iness is a good word to remember. I hope you know how much I love you.
